</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="3" type="epitype">
<paragraph pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Epitype.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="2" pageNumber="3">
An individual on preparation BM18530, from 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Kützing">Kuetzing</normalizedToken>
packet 333, in the Natural History Museum (BM), designated by 
<bibRefCitation author="Tuji, A" journalOrPublisher="Diatom" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" pagination="49 - 54" publicationUrl="https://www.jstage.jst.go.jp/article/diatom1985/23/0/23_49/_pdf" refId="B22" refString="Tuji, A, 2007. Type examination and typification of Cymbella affinis Kuetz., C. turgidula Grunow and C. uenoi Skvortsov. Diatom 23: 49 - 54, https://www.jstage.jst.go.jp/article/diatom1985/23/0/23_49/_pdf" title="Type examination and typification of Cymbella affinis Kuetz., C. turgidula Grunow and C. uenoi Skvortsov." url="https://www.jstage.jst.go.jp/article/diatom1985/23/0/23_49/_pdf" volume="23" year="2007">Tuji (2007</bibRefCitation>
, Fig. 9).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="3" type="epitype locality">
<paragraph pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Epitype locality.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="2" pageNumber="3">
Falaise, France, coll. De 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Brébisson">Brebisson</normalizedToken>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="2" pageNumber="3">
Valvae lanceolate, dorsiventral, dorsal and ventral margins convex; ends barely protracted, rounded, to slightly subrostrate or subcapitate; length 22.5-26.5 
<normalizedToken originalValue="µm">µm</normalizedToken>
, breadth 7.0-8.5 
<normalizedToken originalValue="µm">µm</normalizedToken>
, L/B ratio 2.9-3.4; axial area narrow, linear-arched, indistinct central area; striae 9-12 in 10 
<normalizedToken originalValue="µm">µm</normalizedToken>
, becoming 11-18 towards ends, one isolated pore at end of central striae on ventral side; 19-27 punctae in 10 
<normalizedToken originalValue="µm">µm</normalizedToken>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="3" type="remarks">
<paragraph pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="2" pageNumber="3">
Although 
<bibRefCitation author="Krammer, K" journalOrPublisher="Diatoms of Europe" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" pagination="1 - 584" refId="B7" refString="Krammer, K, 2002. Diatoms of the European inland waters and comparable habitats. Cymbella. Diatoms of Europe 3: 1 - 584" title="Diatoms of the European inland waters and comparable habitats. Cymbella." volume="3" year="2002">Krammer (2002</bibRefCitation>
, p. 41) used material sampled by the same collector and from the same locality and related his new preparation to the type locality, his effort did not constitute a typification of 
<taxonomicName authority="" authorityName="Kuetz" authorityYear="1844" class="Bacillariophyceae" family="Cymbellaceae" genus="Cymbella" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Cymbella affinis" order="Cymbellales" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" phylum="Bacillariophyta" rank="species" species="affinis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Cymbella affinis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as ruled by the ICN (Art. 7.10, 
<bibRefCitation author="McNeill, J" journalOrPublisher="Koeltz Scientific Books, Koenigstein" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" pagination="1 - 240" refId="B14" refString="McNeill, J, Barrie, FR, Buck, WR, Demoulin, V, Greuter, W, Hawksworth, DL, Herendeen, PS, Knapp, S, Marhold, K, Prado, J, Prud'Homme Van Reine, WF, Smith, GF, Wiersema, JH, Turland, NJ, 2012. International Code of Nomenclature for algae, fungi, and plants (Melbourne Code) adopted by the Eighteenth International Botanical Congress Melbourne, Australia, July 2011. Koeltz Scientific Books, Koenigstein: 1 - 240" title="International Code of Nomenclature for algae, fungi, and plants (Melbourne Code) adopted by the Eighteenth International Botanical Congress Melbourne, Australia, July 2011" year="2012">McNeill et al. 2012</bibRefCitation>
). On the other hand, 
<bibRefCitation author="Tuji, A" journalOrPublisher="Diatom" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" pagination="49 - 54" publicationUrl="https://www.jstage.jst.go.jp/article/diatom1985/23/0/23_49/_pdf" refId="B22" refString="Tuji, A, 2007. Type examination and typification of Cymbella affinis Kuetz., C. turgidula Grunow and C. uenoi Skvortsov. Diatom 23: 49 - 54, https://www.jstage.jst.go.jp/article/diatom1985/23/0/23_49/_pdf" title="Type examination and typification of Cymbella affinis Kuetz., C. turgidula Grunow and C. uenoi Skvortsov." url="https://www.jstage.jst.go.jp/article/diatom1985/23/0/23_49/_pdf" volume="23" year="2007">Tuji (2007)</bibRefCitation>
was the first to consider the original material of this taxon and performed a lectotypification and epitypification, and as such, must be followed according to Articles 9.19 and 9.20 (
<bibRefCitation author="McNeill, J" journalOrPublisher="Koeltz Scientific Books, Koenigstein" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" pagination="1 - 240" refId="B14" refString="McNeill, J, Barrie, FR, Buck, WR, Demoulin, V, Greuter, W, Hawksworth, DL, Herendeen, PS, Knapp, S, Marhold, K, Prado, J, Prud'Homme Van Reine, WF, Smith, GF, Wiersema, JH, Turland, NJ, 2012. International Code of Nomenclature for algae, fungi, and plants (Melbourne Code) adopted by the Eighteenth International Botanical Congress Melbourne, Australia, July 2011. Koeltz Scientific Books, Koenigstein: 1 - 240" title="International Code of Nomenclature for algae, fungi, and plants (Melbourne Code) adopted by the Eighteenth International Botanical Congress Melbourne, Australia, July 2011" year="2012">McNeill et al. 2012</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="2" pageNumber="3">
The lectotype valve of 
<taxonomicName authority="" authorityName="Kuetz" authorityYear="1844" class="Bacillariophyceae" family="Cymbellaceae" genus="Cymbella" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Cymbella affinis" order="Cymbellales" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" phylum="Bacillariophyta" rank="species" species="affinis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Cymbella affinis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is similar to the lectotype valve of 
<taxonomicName authority="" authorityName="" class="Bacillariophyceae" family="Cymbellaceae" genus="Cymbella" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Cymbella excisa" order="Cymbellales" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" phylum="Bacillariophyta" rank="species" species="excisa">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Cymbella excisa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, except for the excision in the middle part of the valve present in the majority of specimens (Figs 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 1–28" captionStartId="F1" captionText="Figures 1 - 28. Cymbella affinis species complex 1 - 7 Cymbella affinis Kuetz. var. affinis 8 - 14 Cymbella affinis var. excisa (Kuetz.) Grunow, specimens from Trieste in preparation BM 18543 11 Lectotype, designated here 15 - 21 Cymbella affinis var. excisa [- Cymbella excisa sensu Krammer], specimens from Trieste in preparation 1131 IOK 16 Isolectotype, designated here 22 - 28 Cymbella affinis var. neoprocera W. Silva, specimens from Germany in preparation 212 A IOK, holotype 22 Lectotype, designated here. Scale bar: 10 µm." figureDoi="10.3897/phytokeys.53.4782.figures1-28" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/47588" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">8-21</figureCitation>
). Populations of this complex from different parts of the world may or may not have excisions, but this character is present in the majority of specimens from the populations examined (
<bibRefCitation author="Krammer, K" journalOrPublisher="Diatoms of Europe" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" pagination="1 - 584" refId="B7" refString="Krammer, K, 2002. Diatoms of the European inland waters and comparable habitats. Cymbella. Diatoms of Europe 3: 1 - 584" title="Diatoms of the European inland waters and comparable habitats. Cymbella." volume="3" year="2002">Krammer 2002</bibRefCitation>
). Therefore, we consider 
<taxonomicName authority="" authorityName="" class="Bacillariophyceae" family="Cymbellaceae" genus="Cymbella" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Cymbella excisa" order="Cymbellales" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" phylum="Bacillariophyta" rank="species" species="excisa">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Cymbella excisa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="" authorityName="Kuetz" authorityYear="1844" class="Bacillariophyceae" family="Cymbellaceae" genus="Cymbella" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Cymbella affinis" order="Cymbellales" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" phylum="Bacillariophyta" rank="species" species="affinis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Cymbella affinis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as belonging to the same species with differences at the varietal rank based on phenotypic expression and ecological modifications. Genetic studies are still to be completed.
</paragraph>
